# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-australian-football-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In Asia, Australian rules football dates back to 1910 but was only sporadically played until the 1980s after which it has boomed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Clubs have begun in most Asian countries and a governing body for the region, **AFL Asia** was formed in 2008 to coordinate the Asian Championship and promote its affiliated leagues.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] AFL Asia estimates that there are now more than 10,000 Australian Football players across the continent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There are now several regional leagues including the South China Australian Football League (SCAFL) (2011); South East Asia Australian Football League (SEAAFL) (2013); Guangdong Australian Football League (GDAFL) and North East Asia Australian Football League (NEAAFL) (2014).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The main tournament and cup competition is the annual Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Played every year since 2000 this international tournament is the pinnacle of Asian Australian football calendar.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It currently comprises teams from over a dozen countries contesting for Asia's greatest trophy.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It is also emerging as a spectator sport, with professional Australian Football League matches attracting paying audiences, record attendance was set in Japan with 25,000 attending a 1986 exhibition match at Yokohama Stadium.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] China has hosted AFL matches at Jiangwan Stadium since 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The most prominent player born in Asia is Australian Football Hall of Fame member Peter Bell (of South Korea) while the most prominent locally developed player is Michito Sakaki (of Japan).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules is broadcast into Asia on satellite television through the Australia Network.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football in Japan was first introduced in 1910.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] McLean founded the Seisoka Football Club and was successful in introducing it as a sport to four large high schools in Tokyo by having the rules translated into Japanese.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] McLean had hoped to select a national team, however met with a lack of assistance from Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] McLean returned to Australia and Sydney in 1912 and it is not known if the game survived his departure.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] During the wars, matches were played primarily by Australian servicemen in several countries including Indonesia, Malaysia, Japan, Vietnam and South Korea.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Before this time, only informal matches had been played in some countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A rare example involving participants from other countries was the 1941 game held in Port Dickson, British Malaya.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The sport has been organised in Asia since the late 1980s with teams based in Australian expatriate communities and around universities, such as in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There existed an informal association for various Asian AFL clubs for some time, but on 27 July 2013 a meeting of Asia's presidents was held in Bangkok to discuss the future of footy in Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In all, 13 countries / clubs attended and submissions were received from a further four clubs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] This was the first time representatives of Asian Australian Rules football had ever met with the sole purpose of preparing a road map for Asian footy.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] This meeting lead to the formation of AFL Asia, the official Association for Australian Football in Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The most recent Asian Champions are the Malaysian Warriors who defeated the Philippine Eagles in Manila, Philippines on 21 October 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The 2018 AFL Asian Championships will be held in Kuala Lumpur on October 13, 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian and New Zealand soldiers have (in the past) played games of Australian rules football in Afghanistan, most notably on ANZAC Day.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Brunei since 1998 when a social match was held, followed by a meeting to establish the Brunei Australian Rules Football League.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Anthony Rodaughan was duly appointed the League's first president.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The domestic competition soon commenced at the Jerudong International School soccer field, with a three-team competition including players from England, Scotland, New Zealand, Canada and Brunei.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Late 1998/99 saw huge changes in the fledgling competition as the country began ending numerous expat contracts.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Player numbers were reduced but the league took stock and continued to provide a regular competition for its members.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] 1999 brought the formation of the Brunei Sharks, a composite side representing the league, playing their first match against the Singapore Wombats.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Sharks' first appearance at the Asian Australian Football Championships was in 2000 in Jakarta.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Cambodia by members of the expatriate Australian community in Phnom Penh since around 2000, when a club nicknamed the Cambodia Crocodiles was formed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Crocodiles hosted other teams from around the Asian region for at least one tournament, but then went into recess.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A new club, now known as the Cambodian Kangas, was under formation in 2008, hosting a four-team Indochina Cup in Phnom Penh in November of that year, but this club also did not last beyond their first tournament.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2010, the Cambodian Cobras formed, hosting the Vietnam Swans in Phnom Penh on July 31.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Cambodian Cobras went from strength to strength in 2011, signing a partnership with the Australian Football League club, The West Coast Eagles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Cobras changed their name to the Cambodian Eagles and participated in their first Asian Champs in the same year.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A number of Cambodian Australians play for the Southern Dragons in the Southern Football League in Melbourne.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Cambodian Eagles went on to win the 2016 ICC where BJ Fitzgerald was named player of the tournament.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football has been played in China since the 1990s, and is currently played by senior clubs in Guangzhou, Shanghai, Tianjin and Beijing, with the Beijing AFL metro league beginning in 2009.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There are also clubs in the special economic development zones of Hong Kong and Macau that play against Chinese teams from Guangzhou and Guangdong in the South China Australian Football league (SCAFL), since 2011.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A representative team of mainly expatriate Australian players has represented China under the names "China Blues" or "China Reds" in competitions such as the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The first representative team composed entirely of Chinese nationals appeared at the 2008 Australian Football International Cup, competing as the *China Red Demons*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Since 2011 it has been known as *Team China*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Australian Football League AFL exhibition match in Shanghai in 2010 and a series of AFL Premiership matches was played there from 2017 to 2019, the first outside of Pacific.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The sport began after the independence of Timor-Leste in 1999 due to Australian Defence Force personnel stationed in the country.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The East Dili Eels were founded around this time.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2001 an organisation named the Timor Lorosa'e Austrálian Futebal Associacao (TILAFA, English: East Timorese Australian Football Association) was formed in Dili and there were plans to send a team to the Arafura Games in Darwin, although this organisation later disappeared.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2007, an exhibition match was played between the ISF (International Stabilisation Force) Tigers from the ADF and the UN Police Warriors (Jumpers borrowed from the NT Team Waratah Warriors).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Both teams had female players and local Timorese players, played at Democracy Field in Dili, which was constructed by the Combat Engineers, this match was the culmination of several Auskick clinics over two months where up to one hundred kids participated.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The match raised $10,000 US for the Mary Mackillop Foundation and went to the local, underprivileged people of Timor.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2008 Luke Gosling and Justin Bayard helped start the Timor-Leste Australian Rules Football Club.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The club managed to work with the Northern Territory Football League and Australian Volunteers International to get locals playing the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A national team was created in 2008, though not in time to get to the 2008 International Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2008, the East Timor Crocodiles team formed, making their debut at the 2008 Bali 9s tournament.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A governing body, AFL Timor-Leste, was created in 2011 to facilitate sending a team to that year's International Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] East Timor, playing as *Timor-Leste* participated in its first International Cup in 2011.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The team did participate in 2011 however not win a game and did not return.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Lin Jong, of East Timorese heritage, debuted in 2011 and received a congratulatory letter from Timor Leste Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Jong served as an AFL Multicultural Ambassador and ambassador for the East Timor Hearts Fund.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Hong Kong is home to one of Asia's oldest and most successful Australian rules football clubs, the Hong Kong Dragons having played their first match in 1990.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Based primarily around expat Australians, the club plays frequent matches against other clubs in the Asian region, including other teams from mainland China.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Hong Kong Dragons have won the coveted AFL Asian Championships title six times, in 2003, 2004, 2007, 2012, 2013, 2015.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Hong Kong local teams also play in the South China Australian Football league where they play against teams from southern mainland China and Macau.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Hong Kong also have an active Auskick community with over 400 children participating in Auskick and the HK Junior AFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Spread over 5 centres across Hong Kong teams train weekly and regularly play against other teams.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The representative team HK Junior Dragons also annually play against the Singapore Sharks and tour Australia playing against Australian local teams and half time at professional AFL games.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Hong Kong Vikings Masters teams born out of Dads from the Junior Auskick centres have been training together in growing numbers and internal Reds v Whites AFL 9's games, social events and once a year play against the Hong Kong Dragons.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In July 1940, a match was played at Kowloon at the Police Club grounds.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Known locally as "footy", it is played in India and the country has participated in the International Cup since 2008.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] However India is not currently affiliated to AFL Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] India's national Australian rules team is known as the Tigers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The sport is played in more than 12 Indian states, though it is most popular in the eastern states, particularly Jharkhand and West Bengal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The current record attendance is 20,000 set in 2018 up from 6,000 in 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Chakraborty Medal is awarded to the best player from India and is named after Sudip Chakraborty the first member of the Australian Rules Football in India Hall of Fame.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The West Australian Football League toured India in 1969, playing two exhibition matches in New Delhi between East Perth and Subiaco Football Clubs, which attracted large crowds and interest, a record 3,500 spectators turned out for one of the matches.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football began in India with the creation of the Indian Amateur Australian Football Association in 2001.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The organisation was based in Delhi, but disbanded in 2004.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The potential for the game has several times attracted interest from Australia, with the WAFL in 2005 proposing an exhibition match for Mumbai.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The next appearance of organised Australian rules in India came with the visit of Brian Dixon to Kolkata in 2006 which resulted in the formation of starter clubs in the city and a platform for the development of an Indian team for the 2008 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The first Indian national team was drawn from players recruited by the AFL India in Kolkata, as well as Indian nationals living in Melbourne.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2008 Ricky Ponting launched Australian Rules Football in India (ARFAI) in Kolkata after he and Shane Warne had popularised the sport while playing with the Kolkata Knight Riders.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian expatriate Lincoln Harris kickstarted a junior competition in Mumbai in 2010.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A major tournament was promoted in 2012 featuring Steve Waugh as Australian patron.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Richmond Football Club (Tigers) expressed strong interest in holding an AFL exhibition match in India in 2008.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The idea has been furthered by the club in 2012 and 2018, although plans were put on hold during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2017, the Bharat Warriors Football Club were founded in Melbourne with the aim of recruiting players of Indian origin to promote Australian rules football in India.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The club operates exchange programs between Australia and India.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Despite no AFL matches being staged, a match held in 2017 between the Indian national team and an Australian AFL Masters side attracted over 6,000 spectators at Paschim Medinipur district (West Midnapore).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In April 2018, AFLW player Jess Dal Pos visited Mumbai to conduct young girls clinics in the sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2018, 20,000 people attended a national championships match at Similipal Mini Stadium in Bholagoria.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] With play resuming post-COVID-19, Australians have been called in to officiate matches including the AFL India Championships due to a lack of officials in the country to cope with the growth.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2023, India Warriors made a three-peat in the TAC Unity Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football was played in Indonesia by Australian soldiers in 1945 in Morotai and also Ngada.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It is currently played in Indonesia by clubs in Jakarta (formed in 1995), Bali (formed in 1997) and the Borneo Bears based in Balikpapan, these three clubs being mainly made up of expatriate Australians.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There is also a league consisting of local villagers around the Pancawati area in West Java.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Jakarta Bintangs and Bali Geckos regularly contest the Java-Bali Cup and participate in the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A club was under formation as of 2006 in Banda Aceh, although this project was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Founded in 2003, the West Java Australian Football League (WeJAFL) has over 500 local junior and senior players in the local competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The large number of local players makes it the Asian nation with the highest participation rate amongst locals, and the club sent an Indonesian team, the Indonesian Garudas, composed of members of all the Indonesia clubs to the Australian Football International Cup in 2014.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Jakarta Bulldogs Australian Football Club, established in late 2006, is an Aussie Rules Football Club made up of primarily of Under 18 year old expatriate and local students from the British International School Jakarta, although they share no affiliation with the school.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The club was founded by Australian-born brothers Alf Eddy (Club Captain) and Max Eddy (Head Coach) and has played against a wide variety of local Australian Football teams such as the Pancawati Eagles, Depok Garudas, the Bandung-New Guinea AFC and the Jakarta Bintangs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Since 2006 the club has gone from strength to strength obtaining full sponsorship from ANZ Bank which allowed for the acquisition of proper uniforms of AFL standard and new footies in 2007.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2008 Bulldogs will take part in the inaugural Junior Asian Championships, going into the competition with high expectations from all involved.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A Finnish member of the club, Tuomas Anttila, was scouted to play with the Finnish national team at the 2008 International Cup, but was unable to make the journey.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Borneo Bears were formed in Balikpapan in 2008, making their debut at the 2008 Bali 9s tournament.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Indonesia's national team is known as the Garudas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football in Indonesia receives regular coverage from the Jakarta Globe and is now regularly played on television via the Australia Network including live coverage of the AFL Grand Final.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football in Japan is coordinated by the AFL Japan, with a national league based mainly in Tokyo (affiliated with the Australian Football League) but with clubs in Osaka, Nagoya and Hiroshima.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Development teams from the AFL Japan regularly tour to Australia and have competed at all Australian Football International Cups to date.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Lao Elephants were formed in Vientiane in 2007, as the first Australian Rules Football club in Laos.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The team played their first international fixture against the Vietnam Swans and Thailand Tigers in November 2007 in Hanoi.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Lao Elephants impressed many by defeating archrivals Vietnam and Thailand on debut at the Asian Australian Football Championships in Singapore in September 2008.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Later, the "Phants" were victorious in the Mekong Cup held in Phnom Penh, Cambodia on 22 November 2008, involving the Cambodian Kangaroos, Thailand Tigers, Vietnam Swans and Lao Elephants.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The first domestic match in Laos was held in May 2009, with the Northerners (squad members based in Vientiane and Luang Prabang) defeating the Southerners (mine workers from the Sepon area) in Savannakhet.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Macau Lightning AFL club was formed in 2009 and began running Auskick Clinics at the International School of Macau.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] With an increasing demand for more football from the kids participating, the club started Saturday morning training which continues to grow with boys and girls aged between 4 and 13 years.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In September 2010 the Macau Lightning Auskick played their first match against the Hong Kong Auskick marking the first of many future match days between both clubs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It was a small beginning for the Senior Macau Lightning Team in 2009 with only a handful of guys looking for a social kick.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] As word spread of AFL in Macau numbers gradually grew to a competitive squad of 30 players by May 2010.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] 2010 has seen the Senior Team make their International Debut with matches against Hong Kong Dragons in May, touring to Guangzhou in August and participating in the China Cup against the Hong Kong Dragons and the China Reds in early September.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] On April 13, 2013, the Lightning achieved their greatest team feat thus far in the short existence defeating both the Hong Kong Blues and a combined Hong Kong team in Round 4 of the SCAFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football is regularly played in Malaysia, currently the main Australian Rules Football team is the Malaysian Warriors who will play four home and four away games in 2015 as well as the Manila Cup tournament and the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The earliest known history of Australian rules football in Malaysia goes back to the Australian armed forces (2/19th battalion) playing at Port Dickson in 1941.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian servicemen also attempted to introduce the code to Malays at Penang in 1958 and 1963.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Regular games have been played since the late 1980s in Kuala Lumpur, primarily by expatriate Australians living and working in the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The club was initially known as the MARK Tigers (Malaysian Australian Rules Kelab) and the team played their first game in February 1993 against Hong Kong in Kuala Lumpur and first toured to Singapore in July 1993.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] They recorded their first win in August 1994 against a team from the Royal Australian Air Force base in Butterworth, Penang.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Between 1994 and 1998, the club became consistent contenders on and off the field in Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Games were mainly played against the RAAF in Penang, the Singapore Wombats and the Jakarta Bintangs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Asian economic crisis of 1998 saw many members of the Australian community in Malaysia return home, leaving the club in great difficulties.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2000 the team reformed under a new name, the Malaysian Warriors and have played continually since.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Warriors also participate in an annual five match series of International Rules games against the Orang Éire Gaelic Football Club.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The most notable results for the Warriors to date have been the 2012 Manila Cup winners, Premiers of Asia in 2013 and 2015, and runner up in the 2015 Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Warriors train at Padang Merbok, located near the Lake Gardens, Kuala Lumpur.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] More recently ex AFL players Daniel Chick and Tim Fleming have played games for the Warriors, with Fleming scoring 7 goals in a game against Jakarta which Malaysia went on to win to retain the 'Batik Cup'.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Warriors had an unbeaten 2015 season before the Asian Australian Football Championships and finished on top of the AFL Asia ladder.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2016 they contested the Manila Cup and the 2016 Asian Australian Football Championships as well as various home and away games most notably the 2016 Anzac Day clash against the Thailand Tigers in Kanchanaburi.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Mongolian Wolves joined Asian Australian Football Championships in 2019.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The first matches in Nepal were played in 2013 by the *Thyangboche Yaks* and local children also began playing.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] More regular matches were later played and the *Himalayan Leopard* club were formed around 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Further growth was facilitated by the Association of Nepalese Alumni from Australia, and Nepal was granted entry to AFL Asia in 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football began in 2014 and has grown rapidly.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It was first introduced by Chaudrey Zulfiqar Ali and Tayyab Chattha with support from the Australian High Commission.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Teams were established in Islamabad, Rawalpindi, Multan and Gujranwala.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The code in Pakistan benefits greatly from access to full sized grounds with cricket there being the most popular sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It is currently strongest in the Swat Valley, where a large competition operates and draws large enthusiastic crowds.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] AFL Pakistan (connected with an anti-drug charity network) was formed to govern the sport and select the national team, which has participated in the Australian Football International Cup every tournament since 2014.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A major national tournament was organised in 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australia sent a coach to assist Pakistan in 2019 however the sport's rapid growth in popularity was greatly outpacing local officials ability to support it.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] 10 of Pakistan's more than 15 clubs contested the 2021 AFL Pakistan National Championships in Islamabad.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Islamabad Tigers have been the dominant club with 5 national titles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Pakistan sent a team to the Asian Championship in 2022, however met some roadblocks to participation due to funding.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Despite challenges sending a team, it won the Division 3 title.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2022 AFL Asia reported that Pakistan was the largest and fastest growing nation for the sport in Asia with over 5,000 players with a 45% annual increase in participation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] From a handful of clubs in 2014, AFL Pakistan grew to over 15 clubs in 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Philippine Australian Football League (PAFL) was created in 2004.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Trimmers and Bangers are considered the greatest players in the PAFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The league currently runs a two-team competition in Manila.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The teams, the Dingoes and the Eureka's, were originally based on the division of Victorian (Eurekas) and Non-Victorian (Dingoes) players, but with expansion that divide has not been followed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] PAFL hosted the 2005 and 2014 Asian Australian Football Championships, its representative side is known as the Philippine Eagles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Eagles won their first AFL Asian Championships in 2016 in Vietnam.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football started in Singapore in April 1993, when a group from the Australian expatriate community founded the Singapore Lions (later Wombats) Australian Football Club.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Singapore Wombats play matches throughout each year against visiting Royal Australian Navy ships, as well as a number of tour matches against other expat-based teams from around Asia in the AFL Asia League and the Bali Masters.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] 2007 for Junior and Auskick players and since 2014 Masters/Dads team was added.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Sharks juniors play weekly at the Australian International School (AIS) on Lorong Chuan, Singapore and have toured to Australia, Shanghai, Hong Kong and played at half time of several professional AFL games.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules was played in South Korea during the Korean War.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] On August 29, 1950, Australians stationed on the USS Bataan (CVL-29) introduced it, playing along with locals in front of bemused onlookers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australians and New Zealanders played further matches in 1951.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 1953, VFL matches were broadcast to Australian troops stationed in Korea via radio.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 1954, Australians stationed in South Korea built a dedicated Australian rules football ground and played matches of both football and also used the ground to play cricket against the English.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] South Korean born Peter Bell debuted in the Australian Football League in 1995 and played 286 games and kicked 250 goals during his AFL career in which he was Fremantle Football Club captain, played in 2 AFL Premierships and was two time All-Australian.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] AFL South Korea was formed in 2022 and became a member of AFL Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules was introduced to Sri Lanka in 2016 and the country participated in the 2017 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Interest in Australian rules in Sri Lanka dates back to 1910, with a failed proposal for the Young Australia League to tour Colombo.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A group of AFL officials met with the country's Minister of Internal Trade & Cooperatives, Johnston Fernando in 2010.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Manel Dharmakeerthie and Milton Amarasinghe, a former Director General of Sports, worked together to develop Australian Football in Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Their first aim is a tournament to be held in 2011.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Fernando was supportive of their plans, and has agreed to offer, "his fullest support to develop footy (in Sri Lanka)." Several current and former AFL players were also present at the meeting, including the AFL's new International Ambassador, Brett Kirk.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The players are in Sri Lanka to learn more about that country's indigenous Vadda people and their place in Sri Lankan society, in an attempt to assist Australia's own indigenous communities upon their return.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Cricketer Ricky Ponting who popularised the sport on the sub continent in 2008.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Sri Lanka affiliated with AFL Asia in 2018 along with Nepal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Thailand since the 1990s with the creation of the Thailand Tigers by Australians living in the city of Bangkok.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Tigers run a domestic social league in Bangkok, as well as competing as the Tigers in regional competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Tigers hosted the 2007 Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Thailand Tigers, was established in the 90's and has grown strong ever since.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The club plays weekly intra-club matches fighting for the inaugural 'Bob & Gerry Cup' (the club founders).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Also playing in international tours including hosting the annual Anzac Day Cup and events such as Indo-China tri-nations and the Asian Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Tigers is now a tradition for expat's from Australia and beyond, extending to the Tigers netball team for the ladies, bringing everyone together regularly for sports and social events.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Family, partners and children are always welcome to Tigers events.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Every year for Anzac Day, the Tigers invite an international club for a special match commemorating the memory of the prisoners-of-war (POW) working on the Hellfire Pass, part of the Burma Railway, during World War II.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The day begins early with both teams attending the dawn service at Hellfire Pass, the moving tribute sets the tone for the day.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The full-time match fielding 14 on field players commences 1:30pm in the full heat of Kanchanaburi close to the Myanmar border.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The match is also attended by the Quiet Lions and VIP guests of the last remaining Diggers (POW's) who attend every year for the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] At the game's end the winning team and best player are presented with their awards by 'Snowy' a tribute to mankind with a genuine Aussie personality.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Anzac Day Cup held in Thailand is open to all public.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Timor Leste since the 1990s with the creation of the Timor Leste Crocodile's by Australians living in the city of Dili.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Australian rules football was first played in Vietnam during the Vietnam War.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A match was played in May 1966 between members of the 5th Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 1971, Australian Force Vietnam (AFV) and 110 Signal Squadron played a match in Saigon organised by Private Conboy of Clifton Hill, Victoria a previous member of Melbourne Football Club Under 19s squad.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Lance corporal Ian Granland of 104 Signal Squadron organised a game of Australian Football at Nui Dat in 1970.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There weren't too many grounds of a suitable size on which the game could be played, but luckily it was learned that there was one within the Task Force Area in the area of 1 Australian Reinforcement Unit.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Lance corporal Geoff Morris and Granland did a recce and located the ground.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It was big enough for Australian Football and it even had posts erected but the grass literally ranged from 20 cm to 1m in height.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] That meant that it would have to be cut!
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In the meantime Granland organised a game against 106 Field Workshops.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Word of mouth informed the two that 105 Field Battery had an old Massey Ferguson Tractor with which they used to tow their guns around, plus a slasher.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Permission to use it for mowing the ground was given.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Morris became the driver and the machine was driven over to the field and he began driving it round and round.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] He got the grass down reasonably short but certainly not bowling green stuff however good enough.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The mowing had to be done the day before the game because any earlier and the grass would have grown significantly enough to require another cut.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] This was pre centre square and 50m arcs so a hand mower was used for the goal squares, centre circle and boundary.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Lance Corporal Granland umpired the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The players turned up in their Land Rovers and trucks.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] What jumpers they wore is till a mystery but it certainly wasn't 'skins v shirts'.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There were players of all ages, size and shape and some bloody good footballers amongst them too.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A photograph of this game would be a gem today.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The umpire copped a bit of abuse from the opposition but that was par for the course.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It was in the days of the one central umpire.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The out of bounds on the full rule had only just been introduced and of course it was applied.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Some of the older heads were not too happy but recognized that it had become a law of the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Many of the blokes who had probably been pretty fair footballers in their youth but now in their late thirties or so they were no match for youth and speed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Some of these tried to slow the youngsters down by wacking them but the umpire was on top of that.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] There was no function after the match or anything, just back to the units.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] But, it was a good relief because obviously everyone who played etc. just loved the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Organised Australian rules football has been played in Vietnam since 1998 when the Saigon Saints, was formed by expatriate Australians.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] It was followed shortly after by new rivals the Hanoi Hawks, also established by Australian expatriates.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Saigon Saints stopped playing in 2001.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2003, footy was reborn in Hanoi under the Hanoi Swans banner with a tri-nations tournament against Hong Kong and Thailand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2007, a movement started in Saigon to get footy up again with the goal of combining with Hanoi to form a national team, the Vietnam Swans.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In July 2007, the Vietnam Swans, played together for the first time in Bangkok for the 8th Annual Asian Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] They returned to the Asian Championships in 2008 in Singapore and have been playing ever since.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2009, highlights included the ANZAC Day Match against the Thailand Tigers at Hellfire Pass on the Death Burma Railway; a Black Saturday Tribute Match and Fundraiser against the Bali Geckos a match against HMAS *Darwin* and the Asian Championships.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A team drawn from the Melbourne Vietnamese community also competed in the Australian Football Multicultural Cup in both years of the competition's existence (2004, 2005) and has competed against touring teams from the Japan Samurai.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Members of this team have expressed interest in working to develop Aussie Rules amongst local players in Vietnam, with plans to visit Hanoi for matches against the Vietnam Swans.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] Players from this squad eventually formed the Elgar Park Dragons, a team mainly made up of Vietnamese-Australians affiliated with Box Hill North in the Victorian Amateur Football Association.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] In 2009, the Dragons became a stand-alone club under the name Southern Dragons, moving to the Southern Football League.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] The Dragons have since moved back to the VAFA.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/afl-asia] A number of Vietnamese members of the Elgar Park Dragons also played for Team Asia at the 2008 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is the largest city of Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] While politically independent from the province, it is usually grouped by the Philippine Statistics Authority therewith for statistical purposes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles City is the urban core of Metro Clark, an urban area in Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] This area, also known as Metro Angeles, is considered the industrial and residential heartland of Central Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Metro Clark-Angeles is also identified as a regional center by the national government.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In 1796, the *gobernadorcillo* or town head of San Fernando, *Don* Ángel Pantaleón de Miranda, and his wife, *Doña* Rosalía de Jesús, along with some followers, staked out a new settlement, which they named *Culiát* because of the abundance of vines (*Gnetum indicum*) of that name in the area.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The new settlers cleared the woodland and cultivated the area for rice and sugar farming.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Don Ángel built his first house with light materials at the northwest corner of the intersection of Sapang Balen and the road going towards the town of Porac.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was later donated to the Catholic Church and became a cemetery called "Campo Santong Matua" (today the site of Nepomuceno Coliseum).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] On May 12, 1812, the new settlers tried to make Culiat a self-governing town but the friars resisted the move, led by Fray José Pometa.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Ten years later, on February 11, 1822, Don Ángel filed a petition for the township of Culiat to secede from San Fernando, but it was denied.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] This was followed by another petition within the same year, jointly signed by Don Ángel, his son-in-law, Mariano Henson, and the latter's father, Severino Henson.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] He donated 35 hectares (86 acres) for the construction of the first Catholic church, a convent and a primary school while Doña Agustina Henson de Nepomuceno, the niece of who would become the first **gobernadorcillo** of Angeles in 1830, Don Ciriaco de Miranda, gave land for the new public market.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Don Ángel paid the complete amount required by law just for the secession of Culiat from San Fernando.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] There were only 160 taxpayers then but the law required that it should have at least 500 taxpayers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Located some 10 miles (16 km) north of Pampanga's capital, Culiat became a barrio of San Fernando for 33 years and on December 8, 1829, became a separate municipality.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The newly-autonomous town was renamed "*El Pueblo de los Ángeles*" in honor of its patron saints, the Holy Angels, and the name of its founder, Don Ángel, coinciding with the rise of new *barrios* such as Santo Cristo (as the *población* or town proper), Cutcut, Pampang and Pulong Anunas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The progressive barrios developed some new industries like a sugar mill and a wine distillery.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The transition of Angeles from a jungle clearing to a barrio, to a town and finally to a city took 168 years and in all that time, it survived locusts' infestations, wars, epidemics, volcanic eruptions and typhoons to become one of the fast rising towns in the country.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] When it received its first official municipal charter, the town contained some 661 people, 151 houses and an area of 38.65 km2.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] On May 7, 1899, General Emilio Aguinaldo transferred the seat of the First Philippine Republic to Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It then became the site of celebrations for the first anniversary of Philippine independence, which was proclaimed a year earlier in Kawit, Cavite.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Aguinaldo's sojourn was short, however, for in July of this same year he transferred his government to the province of Tarlac following Angeles' occupation by the American forces.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] On August 10, 1899, U.S. forces began the attack on Angeles confident in capturing it in a few days.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] However, the Filipino Army defending the town refused to give in so easily and fiercely fought back and for three months, they battled the Americans in and around the town.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was only after the battle on November 5, 1899, that the town finally fell into American hands.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Battle of Angeles was considered to be the longest in the history of the Filipino-American War in Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] This led to the establishment of an American camp in Barrio Talimundoc (in what is now Lourdes Sur), located next to the railroad station, in order to establish control over the central plains of Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Civil Government in Angeles by appointing an *alcalde* or municipal mayor, beginning American rule over Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In 1902, the United States Army studied relocating their post from Barrio Talimundoc to a fertile plain in Barrio Sapang Bato, which supposedly had better grass for their horses.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] President Theodore Roosevelt signed an executive order on September 1, establishing 7,700 acres (31 km2) of land in Sapang Bato as Fort Stotsenburg (which later would expand to 156,204 acres (632.14 km2) in 1908 to become Clark Air Base).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was centered on what would in later years become Clark Air Base's parade ground.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Americans quickly commandeered Holy Rosary Parish Church and converted it into an army hospital, with the choir loft served as a dental clinic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The *convento*, which now houses Holy Family Academy, was the barracks for medical officers and enlisted men.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The sacristy was the only portion where Angeleños could hear Mass.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] When the Americans finally vacated the church in 1904 and relocated to Fort Stotsenburg, parish priest Rev.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Vicente Lapus listed a total of US$638 for portions of the church destroyed, looted church items and treasures, and arrears on rentals.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Hours after the attack on Pearl Harbor, Japan attacked the Philippines, targeting the American military presence, as well as the Philippine Army, and taking over the civilian government.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] During the Japanese occupation in the country, 57,000 Filipino and American prisoners of war passed the town of Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] They were forced to join the Bataan Death March, going to Camp O'Donnell in Capas, Tarlac.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeleños showed their sympathy by handing them food, milk, boiled eggs, rice cakes, cigarettes, and water.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeleños followed them up to the train station in Dau railway station in Mabalacat to give moral and spiritual support, and even helped the escapees.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] War historians considered the bombing of Fort Stotsenburg on December 8, 1941, at 12:30 p.m. as one of the most destructive air raids in World War II, because almost all the American war planes were wrecked on the ground.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In thirty minutes, the air might of the United States in the Far East was completely destroyed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] On the early morning of New Year's Day 1942, the first Japanese troops entered Angeles; they would occupy it until January 1945.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] During the Japanese invasion, another type of local government was set up on January 22, 1942.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] During the Japanese occupation, Clark Air Base then became a major center for staging Japanese air operations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Japanese aircraft flying out of Clark participated in the Battle of Leyte Gulf, considered to be the largest naval battle of the Second World War and possibly the largest naval battle in history.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Clark Air Base was recaptured by the Americans in January 1945, after three months of fierce fighting in the Philippines.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] After three years of atrocities committed by Japanese forces, the town and the rest of the Philippines were finally liberated by the combined United States and Philippine Commonwealth troops in 1945.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The building of the general headquarters of the Philippine Commonwealth Army and Philippine Constabulary was situated in Angeles from January 1945 to June 1946, during and after World War II.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] After World War II, the Philippines gained independence from the United States on July 4, 1946, but then would be tied to a neo-colonial relationship.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The "Treaty of General Relations" signed on independence day itself signified the Americans' withdrawal and surrender of possession, control and sovereignty over the Philippines, except the use of their bases.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was followed by the Philippine-American Military Bases Agreement on March 14, 1947, allowing the U.S. to maintain territorial integrity and sovereignty over Clark Air Base and Subic Naval Base for the next 44 years.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Clark occupied 63,103 hectares and served as the tactical operational U.S. air force installation in the entire Southeast Asian region that had the capacity to accommodate the U.S. military transport planes, which served the entire Western Pacific.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Through the years, although Fort Stotsenburg continued to expand to become what would eventually be known as Clark Air Base, Angeles, despite its proximity to the American camp, did not progress fast and remained fairly small until the end of World War II.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was finally inaugurated on January 1, 1964, as a chartered city under Republic Act No.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] 3700 and then proceeded to enter a period of tremendous growth that resulted in its present position as the "Premier City in Central Luzon".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was through Mayor Rafael del Rosario's brainchild that Angeles became a city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] He gained the distinction of being the last municipal mayor of Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] He was assisted in the preparation of the City Chapter by Attorney Enrique Tayag, a prominent resident of the town.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Congresswoman Juanita Nepomuceno of the first district of Pampanga sponsored the bill in Congress, which was approved by then President Diosdado Macapagal, the ninth Philippine president and a native of the province of Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] On June 15, 1991, Angeles was affected by the cataclysmic eruption of nearby Mount Pinatubo, with up to 60,000 people being evacuated from the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was the second-largest volcanic eruption of the twentieth century and, by far, the largest eruption to affect a densely populated area.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The province of Pampanga, Clark specifically, was badly hit and the agricultural lands, as well as other businesses, were covered by tons of lahar.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] There were no casualties reported inside Clark two days from the initial eruption because the 18,000 personnel and their families were transported to Guam and the Subic Naval Base in Zambales.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The eruption of Mount Pinatubo forced the leadership of the U.S. to prematurely abandon its military installation at Clark Air Base.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] This was in addition to a vote by the Philippine Senate in 1991 to no longer extend the Laurel–Langley Agreement, which allowed the presence of U.S. military forces on Philippine territory, thus ending the long chapter of Filipino-American relations in the history of Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In 1993, cleanup and removal of volcanic ash deposits began.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The former base re-emerged as Clark Special Economic Zone (CSEZ) approved by then President Fidel V.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The airfield infrastructure was improved and destined to be the premiere airport in the country in the next five years and one of the most modern in Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The creation of CSEZ has helped to offset the loss of income and jobs previously generated by the presence of the U.S. base.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Today, Angeles and Clark together form the hub for business, industry, aviation and tourism, as well as the entertainment and gaming center of Central Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Among the draws for tourists is the local dish sisig which according to the Center for Kapampangan Studies, originated in this Angeles and has been on the menu since the 1730s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Pampanga is well known as the culinary center of the Philippines.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In 2018, Angeles applied to be a UNESCO Creative City, while it also applied *sisig* into the UNESCO List of Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The applications are currently being processed by UNESCO.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It is bordered by Mabalacat to the north, Mexico to the east, San Fernando to the southeast, Bacolor to the south, and Porac to the southwest and west.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Though the city administers itself autonomously from Pampanga, it is the province's commercial and financial hub.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is served by Clark International Airport in Clark Freeport Zone.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is 83 kilometres (52 mi) from Manila and 17 kilometres (11 mi) from the provincial capital, San Fernando.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Under the Köppen climate classification system, Angeles has a tropical savanna climate that borders on a tropical monsoon climate (Köppen climate classification Aw/Am).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles experiences two distinct seasons: a dry season from November through April, with a wet season from May through October.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] From 1953 to 1991, the mean daily low was 22.6 °C and the mean daily high was 31.3 °C, with June being warmest and January and February being the coolest.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The average annual rainfall is 2026.8 mm.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Typhoons tend to approach from the east during the summer and fall.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In July 1972, Central Luzon experienced a month of nearly continuous rain, resulting in ±2,440 millimetres (96 in) falling on the plain around Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Each barangay consists of puroks and some have sitios.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Anunas is the barangay that houses the city's Koreatown, a chain of Korean establishments along the Fil-Am Friendship Highway.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Anunas is also identified as one of the growth centers of the city, focusing on light industries such as woodcarving and rattan craft.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Balibago is the main entertainment district of Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It contains Casino Filipino Angeles and the famous Fields Avenue tourist belt.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The city's biggest mall, SM City Clark, is also situated in Barangay Malabañas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] These two barangays form the main public market district of the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Pampang Wet Market, San Nicolas Market, Friday Flea Market (locally referred to as Apu), Jumbo Jenra Angeles, Puregold Angeles, and the Angeles Slaughterhouse are found here.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Pampang Wet Market is the largest and most frequented wet market in the province of Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It also attracts people from nearby towns.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Ospital Ning Angeles (ONA), City College of Angeles, Angeles City National High School are located in Pampang.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Pulung Maragul is the barangay that houses the city's government complex, which includes the Angeles City Hall, the Angeles City Hall of Justice, and other government buildings.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It is also the location of the Angeles Exit of the North Luzon Expressway and Marquee Mall, Ayala's first mall in Central Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Marquee Place and Marquee Residences later rose in Pulung Maragul as well, next to the mall.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It is home to most of Angeles' heritage and historical structures such as the Holy Rosary Parish Church, Pamintuan Mansion which is privately owned by Maverick Pamintuan, Bale Herencia, and Museo ning Angeles (former City Hall building).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Holy Angel University, Central Luzon's largest university in terms of population, is also located here.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Plans of declaring the barangay or parts of it a heritage zone are ongoing.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Sapangbato is the largest barangay in Angeles in terms of territory, with a total land area of 104,694 sq. meters and a population of 11,262.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Located northwest of Angeles near Clark Freeport Zone, it is identified as the barangay in Angeles with the highest elevation of 750 feet above sea level.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It is home to Fort Stotsenburg, also known as the Parade Grounds of Clark. apl.de.ap, member of the hip hop group the Black Eyed Peas, hails from Sapangbato.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The famous Puning Hot Springs of Barangay Inararo in Porac are accessed through Sitio Target in Sapangbato.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Kapampangan is the predominant language of the city, along with Tagalog.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles City is also home to the majority of Chinese Filipinos that live in Pampanga, a large portion of these Chinese Filipinos have Philippine Hokkien or (咱人話) as their main language.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Due to the growing Korean population in Angeles City, Korean is also spoken by the Korean expatriates that are residing in Angeles City.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The majority of the population of Angeles is Catholic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] At least two major festivals associated with the Catholic faith are held in October in the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Commemorating the victory of the Spanish fleet over the Dutch Navy in 1646, the La Naval Fiesta is celebrated in honor of the Our Lady of La Naval de Manila with adherents believing that her intercession was instrumental to the Spaniards' naval victory.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Apu Fiesta involves devotees from all over Pampanga making a visit to the Apu shrine to venerate the image of Jesus Christ lying in the sepulchre which is believed to be miraculous by believers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Owing to the presence of the nearby U.S.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Clark Air Force Base and consequent Freeport Zone, many Americans chose to permanently settle in the area, particularly in the Balibago district, and thus Angeles became home to a large colony of expatriates.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] During the American colonial period (1898–1946), more than 800,000 Americans were born in the Philippines, and a large concentration of Filipino mestizos or Filipinos with American ancestry were located in this city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Being home of the former Clark Air Base (once the largest United States military facility outside the continental United States), it was significantly affected by the fallout from the eruption of Mount Pinatubo in 1991.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The economy of Angeles was heavily dependent on the American base at that time.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In 1993, a full cleanup and removal of volcanic ash deposits began and the former U.S. base was transformed into the Clark Special Economic Zone (CSEZ).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The creation of CSEZ has helped to offset the loss of income and jobs previously generated by the presence of the U.S. base in the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Today, Angeles and Clark form the hub for business, industry, aviation, and tourism in the Philippines as well as a leisure, fitness, entertainment and gaming center of Central Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is home to an emerging technology industry.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Its economy is based also on tourism and gambling.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Fields Avenue forms the hub of the night life industry focused in Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] With close proximity to an international airport in Clark Freeport, Angeles is visited by foreigners all year round.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] In the 2000s, the local government of Angeles rebranded the Fields Avenue tourist belt as a high-end destination with fine restaurants and luxury hotels and casinos The finishing of roads, such as the Subic–Clark–Tarlac Expressway, has improved trade and transport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The project connects the industrial, transport and business hubs of Pampanga, Zambales, Bataan and Tarlac.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The project is crucial to bolstering growth in Central Luzon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The city has cottage industries producing rattan furniture, coconuts, and charcoal briquettes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It also has many thriving export businesses in handicrafts, metal crafts, toys, houseware and garments.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Apart from the Clark Freeport Zone, industrial areas include the Angeles Livelihood Village and the Angeles City Industrial Estate.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Call centers present are e-Telecare, CyberCity, Sutherland and IRMC.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Other American IT industries are major employers as well.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The establishment of a number of shopping malls also fueled the city's economy, including SM City Clark, Robinsons Angeles, Jenra Grand Mall, Nepo Mall, Saver's Mall and the Marquee Mall, next to City Hall.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles City houses numerous restaurants that are usually located near the malls and mostly in Nepo Quad which was newly renovated to cater the heightened needs of the population.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The city hosts a street party called the Tigtigan Terakan keng Dalan (lit.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] 'Music and Dancing on the Streets') every October which features musical performances from both amateur and better-known OPM bands.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Through *Presidential Proclamation 696*, October 26, 2024 was declared a special non-working day in celebration of its Tigtigan Terakan Keng Dalan Festival.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The Sisig Festival, locally known as the Sadsaran Qng Angeles, festivities dedicated to the Kapampangan dish *sisig*, used to be held every December.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It was halted in 2008 following the murder of Lucia Cunanan, who was known for promoting the dish.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The festival was revived as a one-day fiesta in April 2017 in association with the Department of Tourism.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is promoted as a gastronomy tourist destination and is billed as the "culinary capital" of the Philippines.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The city is known as a hub for Kampampangan cuisine as well as for its pork sisig.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles is also situated within the perimeter of the Clark Freeport Zone.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] One consequence of the historical presence of a US base (until 1991) is the prostitution industry in Angeles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] From the early days of Clark Air Base, Fields Avenue in Balibago district became an area frequently visited by the U.S. servicemen.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] It is until today widely known as a center for prostitution and sex tourism.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] A BBC article characterized it as "the centre of the Philippines sex industry" and dubbed it "Sin City".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Elsewhere and in later years, Philippine travel publications have described it as the "Entertainment Capital of Central Luzon", "The Filipino Las Vegas", and "Entertainment City".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] As a highly urbanized city in the province of Pampanga, government officials at the provincial level are not voted for by the city.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The provincial government has no political jurisdiction over the local transactions of the city government.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Residents of this city are not allowed to run for positions at the provincial level, except for congressional representation for the 1st District of Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The City of Angeles is governed by a city mayor, designated as its local chief executive, and by a city council as its legislative body in accordance with the Local Government Code.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The mayor, vice mayor, and the city councilors are elected directly in polls held every three years.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Barangays are also headed by elected officials: Barangay Captain, Barangay Council, whose members are called Barangay Councilors.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] The barangays have SK federation which represents the barangay, headed by SK chairperson and whose members are called SK councilors.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] All officials are also elected every three years.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Angeles belongs to the first legislative district of the province of Pampanga.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Currently, the city is represented by Carmelo G.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Lazatin Jr. in the house of representatives.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] in Angeles City, the only Cable TV channel is PEP TV on a cable provider Air Cable Channel 3 SD & 209 in HD.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] There are three radio stations in the city: UFM 105.5, GVAM 792 and GV 99.1.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/angeles-city] Clark International Airport is near the city; it is served by many passenger and cargo airlines, including some international ones.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The **Arafura Games** was a multi-sport event where athletes with a disability compete in the same program as able-bodied athletes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] Competitors from around the world compete in the week-long games held every 2 years in Darwin, Northern Territory, Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] Called a "meeting of Sporting Neighbours", the Arafura Games takes its name from the Arafura Sea, which lies between northern Australia and Southeast Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] Nations along the Arafura Sea originally formed the basis of the Arafura Games, however in recent years countries from further afield have participated, including United States, England, Brazil and Liechtenstein.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] A foundation sport of the Arafura Games, Basketball has grown from a 4 team competition with teams from around the Darwin region to an 8 team international competition with teams from all over the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The Games were known as the Arafura Sports Festival up until 1997.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] These Games were the first ever international sporting festival to have Australian Rules Football as an international competition sport in its own right.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The International Australian Football Council was formed after the 1995 Games, playing an important role in promoting Aussie Rules until dissolving in 2001.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The Arafura Games were cancelled in 2003 due to concern over the SARS virus.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] From 2005 onwards, the Arafura Games included events for athletes with physical disabilities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The 2007 Arafura Games received patronage from the International Paralympic Committee (IPC).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] In 2011, the Arafura Games incorporated the Oceania Paralympic Championships for the sports of athletics, swimming, powerlifting, and table tennis.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The 2013 Arafura Games was cancelled by the newly elected CLP government on 31 October 2012 as it "costs too much to run".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] After an eight-year hiatus, the 2019 Arafura Games were held from 27 April to 4 May 2019.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The 2021 games were postponed until 2023 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, however it was later announced by the then Major Events Minister Natasha Fyles, that all future Arafura Games were to be scrapped.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] Conducted under Federation of International Basketball Associations (FIBA) conditions and Guidelines, Basketball is played at the Darwin Basketball Stadium, Abala Road Marrara, in the Marrara Sporting Complex.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] In recent years, USA squad players from university teams dominated the competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The Northern Territory team have been shaded in the last 4 Arafura Games by the Americans and only their depth on the bench has let them down.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/arafura-games] The Northern Territory have won the Silver medal in the past 4 Arafura games.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The **Asian Australian Football Championships**, also known as the **AFL Asian Championships** or Asian Champs is an annual tournament of Australian rules football between AFL Asia member clubs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The tournament is considered the pinnacle of Asian Australian football calendar and is challenged by a growing number of teams from over a dozen Asian countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The competition consists of 3 open men's divisions, 1 women's division and a juniors division.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] A record 21 teams from 13 countries competed in 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The 2023 event will be contested in Bangkok, Thailand on 9 September at the Thai Polo and Equestrian Club, Chon Buri.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The tournament is played over one day with all teams playing shortened games between 20 and 24 minutes duration, with reduced numbers and smaller field sizes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In each division, each team plays each other once then there is a knock-out finals series including Semi-Finals, Preliminary Final and Grand Final.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] First division is played as a 16-a-side format.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] Second division is played in a 12-a-side format.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] There are 3 Men's Divisions, Women's Division and an All-Asia Cup (only local players allowed).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] The Asian Australian Football Championships were first held in 2000, although a precursor tournament named the Four Nations Cup was held in Bangkok, Thailand in 1999.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] There was an offer in 2005 to make the championships part of the Arafura Games, in Darwin, Australia, but this was turned down by Asian clubs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In 2008 a junior division was introduced, however this was short-lived.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In 2016 an All-Asian Cup was held the day before the Asian Championships with three all-local player teams.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In 2017 a local player quota of 2-players per team was introduced.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In 2015 the tournament was expanded to two divisions, with a 16-a-side first division and a 12-a-side second division.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/asian-australian-football-championships] In 2018 the tournament also included a women's division, with a record 21 teams from 13 countries competing.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] During general play, players may position themselves anywhere on the field and use any part of their bodies to move the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The primary methods are kicking, handballing, and running with the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There are rules on how the ball can be handled; for example, players running with the ball must intermittently bounce or touch it on the ground.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Throwing the ball is not allowed, and players must not get caught holding the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A distinctive feature of the game is the mark, where players anywhere on the field who catch the ball from a kick (with specific conditions) are awarded unimpeded possession.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Possession of the ball is in dispute at all times except when a free kick or mark is paid.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Players can tackle using their hands or use their whole body to obstruct opponents.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Dangerous physical contact (such as pushing an opponent in the back), interference when marking, and deliberately slowing the play are discouraged with free kicks, distance penalties, or suspension for a certain number of matches depending on the severity of the infringement.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game features frequent physical contests, spectacular marking, fast movement of both players and the ball, and high scoring.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The sport's origins can be traced to football matches played in Melbourne, Victoria, in 1858, inspired by English public school football games.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Seeking to develop a game more suited to adults and Australian conditions, the Melbourne Football Club published the first laws of Australian football in May 1859.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian football has the highest spectator attendance of all sports in Australia while the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's only fully professional competition, is the nation's wealthiest sporting body.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The AFL Grand Final, held annually at the 100,000-capacity Melbourne Cricket Ground, is the highest-attended club championship event of any football code.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The sport is also played at amateur level in many countries and in several variations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Its rules are governed by the AFL Commission with the advice of the AFL's Laws of the Game Committee.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian football is known by several nicknames, including Australian rules football, Aussie rules, football and footy.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In some regions, where other codes of football are more popular, the sport is most often called AFL after the Australian Football League, while the league itself also uses this name for local competitions in some areas.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Primitive forms of football were played sporadically in the Australian colonies in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Compared to cricket and horse racing, football was considered a mere "amusement" by colonists at the time, and while little is known about these early one-off games, evidence does not support a causal link with Australian football.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In Melbourne, in 1858, in a move that would help to shape Australian football in its formative years, private schools (then termed "public schools" in accordance with nomenclature in England) began organising football games inspired by precedents at English public schools.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The earliest match, held on 15 June, was between Melbourne Grammar and St Kilda Grammar.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] On 10 July 1858, the Melbourne-based *Bell's Life in Victoria and Sporting Chronicle* published a letter by Tom Wills, captain of the Victoria cricket team, calling for the formation of a "foot-ball club" with a "code of laws" to keep cricketers fit during winter.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Born in Australia, Wills played a nascent form of rugby football while a pupil at Rugby School in England, and returned to his homeland a star athlete and cricketer.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Two weeks later, Wills' friend, cricketer Jerry Bryant, posted an advertisement for a scratch match at the Richmond Paddock adjoining the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This was the first of several "kickabouts" held that year involving members of the Melbourne Cricket Club, including Wills, Bryant, W.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Trees were used as goalposts and play typically lasted an entire afternoon.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Without an agreed-upon code of laws, some players were guided by rules they had learned in the British Isles, "others by no rules at all".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Another milestone in 1858 was a 40-a-side match played under experimental rules between Melbourne Grammar and Scotch College, held at the Richmond Paddock.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Umpired by Wills and teacher John Macadam, it began on 7 August and continued over two subsequent Saturdays, ending in a draw with each side kicking one goal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It is commemorated with a statue outside the MCG, and the two schools have since competed annually in the Cordner–Eggleston Cup, the world's oldest continuous football competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Since the 1920s, it has been suggested that Australian football may have been derived from the Irish sport of Gaelic football.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] However, there is no archival evidence in favour of a Gaelic influence, and the style of play shared between the two modern codes appeared in Australia long before the Irish game evolved in a similar direction.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Another theory, first proposed in 1983, posits that Wills, having grown up among Aboriginals in Victoria, may have seen or played the Aboriginal ball game of Marn Grook, and incorporated some of its features into early Australian football.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There is only circumstantial evidence that he knew of the game, and according to biographer Greg de Moore's research, Wills was "almost solely influenced by his experience at Rugby School".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A loosely organised Melbourne side, captained by Wills, played against other football enthusiasts in the winter and spring of 1858.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The following year, on 14 May, the Melbourne Football Club was officially established, making it one of the world's oldest football clubs.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Three days later, Wills, Hammersley, Thompson and teacher Thomas H.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Smith met near the MCG at the Parade Hotel, owned by Bryant, and drafted ten rules: "The Rules of the Melbourne Football Club".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] These are the laws from which Australian football evolved.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The club aimed to create a simple code suited to the hard playing surfaces around Melbourne, and to eliminate the roughest aspects of English school games—such as "hacking" (shin-kicking) in Rugby School football—to reduce the risk of injuries to working men.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In another significant departure from English public school football, the Melbourne rules omitted any offside law.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] "The new code was as much a reaction against the school games as influenced by them", writes Mark Pennings.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The rules were distributed throughout the colony; Thompson in particular did much to promote the new code in his capacity as a journalist.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Following Melbourne's lead, Geelong and Melbourne University also formed football clubs in 1859.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] While many early Victorian teams participated in one-off matches, most had not yet formed clubs for regular competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A South Yarra club devised its own rules.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] To ensure the supremacy of the Melbourne rules, the first club-level competition in Australia, the Caledonian Society's Challenge Cup (1861–64), stipulated that only the Melbourne rules were to be used.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This law was reinforced by the Athletic Sports Committee (ASC), which ran a variation of the Challenge Cup in 1865–66.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] With input from other clubs, the rules underwent several minor revisions, establishing a uniform code known as "Victorian rules".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1866, the "first distinctively Victorian rule", the running bounce, was formalised at a meeting of club delegates chaired by H.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Harrison, an influential pioneer who took up football in 1859 at the invitation of Wills, his cousin.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game around this time was defensive and low-scoring, played low to the ground in congested rugby-style scrimmages.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The typical match was a 20-per-side affair, played with a ball that was roughly spherical, and lasted until a team scored two goals.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The shape of the playing field was not standardised; matches often took place in rough, tree-spotted public parks, most notably the Richmond Paddock (Yarra Park), known colloquially as the Melbourne Football Ground.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Wills argued that the turf of cricket fields would benefit from being trampled upon by footballers in winter, and, as early as 1859, football was allowed on the MCG.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] However, cricket authorities frequently prohibited football on their grounds until the 1870s, when they saw an opportunity to capitalise on the sport's growing popularity.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Football gradually adapted to an oval-shaped field, and most grounds in Victoria expanded to accommodate the dual purpose—a situation that continues to this day.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Football became organised in South Australia in 1860 with the formation of the Adelaide Football Club, the oldest football club in Australia outside Victoria.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It devised its own rules, and, along with other Adelaide-based clubs, played a variety of codes until 1876, when they uniformly adopted most of the Victorian rules, with South Australian football pioneer Charles Kingston noting their similarity to "the old Adelaide rules".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Similarly, Tasmanian clubs quarrelled over different rules until they adopted a slightly modified version of the Victorian game in 1879.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The South Australian Football Association (SAFA), the sport's first governing body, formed on 30 April 1877, firmly establishing Victorian rules as the preferred code in that colony.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The Victorian Football Association (VFA) formed the following month.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Clubs began touring the colonies in the late 1870s, and in 1879 the first intercolonial match took place in Melbourne between Victoria and South Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1883, delegates representing the football associations of South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Queensland met to standardise the code across Australia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Likewise, when New Zealand experienced a gold rush, the sport arrived with a rapid influx of Australian miners.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Now known as Australian rules or Australasian rules, the sport became the first football code to develop mass spectator appeal, attracting world record attendances for sports viewing and gaining a reputation as "the people's game".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football reached Queensland and New South Wales as early as 1866; the sport experienced a period of dominance in the former, and in the latter, several regions remain strongholds of Australian rules, such as the Riverina.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] However, by the late 1880s, rugby football had become the dominant code in both colonies, as well as in New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This shift was largely due to rugby's spread with British migration, regional rivalries and the lack of strong local governing bodies.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the case of Sydney, denial of access to grounds, the influence of university headmasters from Britain who favoured rugby, and the loss of players to other codes inhibited the game's growth.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1896, delegates from six of the wealthiest VFA clubs—Carlton, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne and South Melbourne—met to discuss the formation of a breakaway professional competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Later joined by Collingwood and St Kilda, the clubs formed the Victorian Football League (VFL), which held its inaugural season in 1897.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The VFL's popularity grew rapidly as it made several innovations, such as instituting a finals system, reducing teams from 20 to 18 players, and introducing the behind as a score.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Richmond and University joined the VFL in 1908, and by 1925, with the addition of Hawthorn, Footscray and North Melbourne, it had become the preeminent league in the country and would take a leading role in many aspects of the sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The time around the federation of the Australian colonies in 1901 saw Australian rules undergo a revival in New South Wales, New Zealand and Queensland.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1903, both the Queensland Australian Football League and the NSW Australian Football Association were established, and in New Zealand, as it moved towards becoming a dominion, leagues were also established in the major cities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This renewed popularity helped encourage the formation of the Australasian Football Council, which in 1908 in Melbourne staged the first national interstate competition, the Jubilee Australasian Football Carnival, with teams representing each state and New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game was also established early on in the new territories.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the new national capital Canberra both soccer and rugby had a head start, but following the first matches in 1911, Australian rules football in the Australian Capital Territory became a major participation sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] By 1981 it had become much neglected and quickly lagged behind the other football codes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football in the Northern Territory began shortly after the outbreak of the war in 1916 with the first match in Darwin.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game went on to become the most popular sport in the Territory and build the highest participation rate for the sport nationally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Both World War I and World War II had a devastating effect on Australian football and on Australian sport in general.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] While scratch matches were played by Australian "diggers" in remote locations around the world, the game lost many of its great players to wartime service.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Some clubs and competitions never fully recovered.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Between 1914 and 1915, a proposed hybrid code of Australian football and rugby league, the predominant code of football in New South Wales and Queensland, was trialled without success.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In Queensland, the state league went into recess for the duration of the war.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] VFL club University left the league and went into recess due to severe casualties.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The West Australian Football League (WAFL) lost two clubs and the SANFL was suspended for one year in 1916 due to heavy club losses.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The Anzac Day match, the annual game between Essendon and Collingwood on Anzac Day, is one example of how the war continues to be remembered in the football community.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The role of the Australian National Football Council (ANFC) was primarily to govern the game at a national level and to facilitate interstate representative and club competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1968, the ANFC revived the Championship of Australia, a competition first held in 1888 between the premiers of the VFA and SAFA.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Although clubs from other states were at times invited, the final was almost always between the premiers from the two strongest state competitions of the time—South Australia and Victoria—with Adelaide hosting most of the matches at the request of the SAFA/SANFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The last match took place in 1976, with North Adelaide being the last non-Victorian winner in 1972.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Between 1976 and 1987, the ANFC, and later the Australian Football Championships (AFC) ran a night series, which invited clubs and representative sides from around the country to participate in a knock-out tournament parallel to the premiership seasons, which Victorian sides still dominated.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] With the lack of international competition, state representative matches were regarded with great importance.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Due in part to the VFL poaching talent from other states, Victoria dominated interstate matches for three-quarters of a century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] State of Origin rules, introduced in 1977, stipulated that rather than representing the state of their adopted club, players would return to play for the state they were first recruited in.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This instantly broke Victoria's stranglehold over state titles and Western Australia and South Australia began to win more of their games against Victoria.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Both New South Wales and Tasmania scored surprise victories at home against Victoria in 1990.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The term "Barassi Line", named after VFL star Ron Barassi, was coined by scholar Ian Turner in 1978 to describe the "fictitious geographical barrier" separating the rugby-following parts of New South Wales and Queensland from the rest of the country, where Australian football reigned.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It became a reference point for the expansion of Australian football and for establishing a national league.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The way the game was played had changed dramatically due to innovative coaching tactics, with the phasing out of many of the game's kicking styles and the increasing use of handball; while presentation was influenced by television.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1982, in a move that heralded big changes within the sport, one of the original VFL clubs, South Melbourne, relocated to Sydney and became known as the Sydney Swans.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the late 1980s, due to the poor financial standing of many of the Victorian clubs, and a similar situation existing in Western Australia in the sport, the VFL pursued a more national competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Two more non-Victorian clubs, West Coast and Brisbane, joined the league in 1987 generating more than $8 million in license revenue for the Victorian clubs and increasing broadcast revenues which helped the Victorian clubs survive.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In their early years, the Sydney and Brisbane clubs struggled both on and off-field because the substantial TV revenues they generated by playing on a Sunday went to the VFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] To protect these revenues the VFL granted significant draft concessions and financial aid to keep the expansion clubs competitive.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The VFL changed its name to the Australian Football League (AFL) for the 1990 season, and over the next decade, three non-Victorian clubs gained entry: Adelaide (1991), Fremantle (1995) and the SANFL's Port Adelaide (1997), the only pre-existing club outside Victoria to join the league.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 2011 and 2012, respectively, two new non-Victorian clubs were added to the competition: Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The AFL, currently with 18 member clubs, is the sport's elite competition and most powerful body.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Following the emergence of the AFL, state leagues were quickly relegated to a second-tier status.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The VFA merged with the former VFL reserves competition in 1998, adopting the VFL name.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] State of Origin also declined in importance, especially after an increasing number of player withdrawals.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The AFL turned its focus to the annual International Rules Series against Ireland in 1998 before abolishing State of Origin the following year.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] State and territorial leagues still contest interstate matches, as do AFL Women players.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the 2010s, the AFL signalled further attempts at expanding into markets outside Australian football's traditional heartlands by hosting home-and-away matches in New Zealand, followed by China.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] After several failed bids since the early 1990s for a Tasmania-based AFL team, the Tasmania Football Club secured the 19th AFL license in 2023, and is set to compete by 2028.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In a standard match, a team may consist of anywhere between 14 and 18 players who may be permitted on the playing surface at any given time.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Each team may have up to four interchange (reserve) players who may be swapped for those on the field at any time during the game, although some leagues in less populated areas may use as few as 12 players.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In addition, some leagues, notably including the AFL, have each team designate one additional player as a substitute who can be used to make a single permanent exchange of players during a game for either medical or tactical reasons.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Players on the playing surface can be swapped with those on the interchange bench at any time.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] They must though pass through a designated "Interchange Area".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the event a player fails to pass through this area correctly, or if too many players from one team are found to be on the ground at a time, a free kick will be awarded to the opposing side.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Players may wear certain pieces of protective equipment, such as helmets or arm guards, if approved by the relevant controlling body.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Mouthguards are strongly recommended for all players.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Players are not permitted to wear jewellery, or other materials which the field umpire has deemed to be either potentially dangerous or increase the risk of injury to other players.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian rules football is played with an ellipsoid ball, between 72 and 73 cm (28 and 29 in) in long circumference, and 54.5 and 55.5 cm (21.5 and 21.9 in) in short circumference.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] For women's competitions, a smaller ball size of 69 and 53 cm (27 and 21 in) is used.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The ball must be inflated to a pressure of 69 kilopascals (10.0 pounds per square inch).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There are no defined laws regarding what material a ball must be made from, but standard AFL match-used balls are produced by Sherrin using cowhide leather.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] While there is no standard colour of the ball, red and yellow are most common and the only colours used at AFL level.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Yellow is used for games beginning after 3 pm or in an enclosed stadium, due to its greater visibility, and to assist score reviews.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Unlike other forms of football which are played on rectangular fields, Australian rules football playing fields are oval-shaped, and are between 135 and 185 metres (148 and 202 yd) long and 110 and 155 metres (120 and 170 yd) wide.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] At either end of the field, two sets of posts are erected in a straight line to indicate the scoring areas on the field, each with two kinds of posts, named the goal posts and the behind posts respectively.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The goal posts are placed first, located 6.4 metres (7.0 yd) apart from each other, with a behind post being placed a further 6.4 metres to the side of each goal post.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The name for the field line between two goal posts is known as the Goal Line.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Around the perimeter of the field, two white lines are drawn between the set of behind posts in an arc-shape, marking the field of play.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The 50m arcs, centre square, centre circle and goal square are used at the beginning of each quarter or after each goal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Each team is permitted a maximum of six players in each 50m arc, with one in the goal square and four players in the centre square with one in the centre circle.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If this is breached, a free kick is awarded.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A game lasts for 80 minutes, split into four quarters consisting of 20 minutes playing time, with the clock being stopped for stoppages in play such as scores, or at the umpire's discretion, e.g. for serious injury.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Leagues may choose to employ shorter quarters of play at their discretion, such as the AFLW using 17 minutes per quarter.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] For any given match, two timekeepers are appointed to officiate the duration.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The timekeepers record all relevant statistics for the match, such as total quarter duration and score by each team.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Additionally timekeepers are required to sound a siren prior to and at the conclusion of each quarter until such time they are acknowledged by the field umpires.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] To stop and recommence the clock, the field umpires are required to signal to the timekeepers to indicate when the clock should be stopped or restarted.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Between each quarter, a break is observed to allow players a rest period.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Two six-minute breaks are observed between the first and second quarters, and the third and fourth quarters.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A longer 20-minute break is observed between the second and third quarter, commonly known as *half-time*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Each game is officiated by at least five match officials, known as an umpire.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] At AFL level, a video score review system is utilised.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Only umpires are permitted to request a review, and only scoring shots and potential scoring shots are permitted to be reviewed.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] An Australian rules football may only be propelled forward in a select few ways as defined by the Laws of Australian Football, published by the AFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The ball can be propelled in any direction by way of a kick or a clenched fist (called a handball)—deemed a correct disposal.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Failure to dispose of the ball in one of these two methods will result in a free kick to the opposing team.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If the ball is not currently in a player's possession, it can be moved legally through the usage of other means, such as punching.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] While in possession of the ball, players may run with the ball, but are required to either bounce or touch the ball on the ground at least once every 15 metres (16 yd).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Tackling is a technique employed by players used to force opposition players to dispose of the ball when they are in possession.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Failure to dispose of the ball when legally tackled may see the player penalised for 'holding the ball', except if the umpire deems there was a lack of prior opportunity to do so.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The ball carrier may only be tackled between the shoulders and knees from the front or side.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If the player forcefully contacts the opposing in the back while performing a tackle, the opposition player will be penalised for a push in the back.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If the opposition tackles the player with possession below the knees (a *low tackle* or a *trip*) or above the shoulders (a *high tackle*), the team with possession of the football gets a free kick.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Furthermore, tackles deemed to be dangerous by the umpire and those conducted from front-on while an opposition player has their head over the football are deemed to be prohibited contact, and will incur a free kick against the offending player.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Additionally, players may perform a technique known shepherding when the ball is within 5 metres (5.5 yd) of an opposition player.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Shepherding involves the use of a player's body to push, bump or otherwise block an opposition player, providing they do not have possession of the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If a player takes possession of the ball that has travelled more than 15 metres (16 yd) from another player's kick, by way of a catch within the field of play, it is deemed as a *mark*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] To be awarded a mark, it must be deemed that the player sufficiently controlled the ball and took possession prior to it being touched, touching the ground, or in the case of a contest, being spoiled by an opponent.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Upon a mark being taken, one opposition player may choose to stand on the point on the field where the mark was taken, known as "the mark".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] When a mark is taken, a small protected zone is established on the field, extending 10 metres (11 yd) either side of "the mark" and the player who marked the ball, with a small protected corridor between "the mark" and the player.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The opposition player is permitted to jump, but is not allowed to move from their position on "the mark".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Any other movements result in a distance penalty (50 metres in the AFL).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The player who was awarded the mark may then choose to either dispose of the ball over "the mark" or may choose to attempt disposal via a different method, in which case the field umpire will call "play on"—a verbal instruction to continue play.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] "Play on" may also be called if the umpire deems the player awarded the mark to be taking an unreasonable amount of time to dispose of the football.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Once the player has disposed of the ball, or "play on" is called, normal play resumes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Rucking is the only specialist skill and is performed by a ruck, the term for designated players from each side to which the umpire sends the ball to commence play.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Only a nominated ruck may contest ball-ups and throw-ins.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] They are the only player allowed within the 10 metre circle at a centre bounce.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Functionally the role is analogous to a basketball centre and as such rucks are typically the tallest player on the team.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Lifting teammates is not allowed so the ruck may only jump to reach the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If the ruck does not take possession of the football, it must be tapped or fisted, which is known as a hit-out.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] An effective hit-out that passes the ball to a teammate is known as a hit-out to advantage.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the event a player breaks a rule, a free kick is awarded to the opposing team, from the location that the misconduct occurred, or the ball's current location—whichever is closer to the team's scoring zone.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] As when a mark is taken, this location is called "the mark", and the same protections regarding the space apply.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the event a player engages in unsportsmanlike conduct after a free kick has been awarded or a mark has been paid to the opposing team, the umpire may instead award a 50-metre penalty.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] When imposed, the field umpire will advance "the mark" an additional 50 metres (55 yd) down the field or to the goal line, whichever is closer.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Additional 50-metre penalties may be awarded if the behaviour continues after the initial penalty.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The laws of the game allow umpires to send off players for egregious foul play, although this law does not apply to the AFL and is largely only used at the local level.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There are two types of scoring shots in Australian football: goals and behinds.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A *goal* is worth six points, and is scored when the football is propelled between the goal posts and across the goal line at any height by way of a kick from the attacking team.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It may touch the ground, but must not have been touched by any player from either team or a goalpost prior to crossing the goal line.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A behind is also awarded to the team if the ball touches any part of an opposition player, including a foot, before passing across their goal or behind line.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] A free kick is awarded against any player who is deemed to have deliberately rushed a behind.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The team that has scored the most points at the end of play wins the game.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] If the scores are level on points at the end of play, then the game is a draw; extra time applies only during finals matches in some competitions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] As an example of a score report, consider a match between Sydney and Geelong with the former as the home team.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Sydney's score of 17 goals and 5 behinds equates to 107 points.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Geelong's score of 10 goals and 17 behinds equates to a 77-point tally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Sydney wins the match by a margin of 30 points.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] "Sydney, seventeen-five, one hundred and seven, defeated Geelong, ten-seventeen, seventy-seven".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The home team is typically listed first and the visiting side is listed second.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The football season proper is from March to August (early autumn to late winter in Australia), with finals being held in September and October.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the tropics, the game is sometimes played in the wet season (October to March).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The AFL is recognised by the Australian Sports Commission as being the National Sporting Organisation for Australian rules.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There are also seven state/territory-based organisations in Australia, all of which are affiliated with the AFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] These state leagues hold annual semi-professional club competitions, with some also overseeing more than one league.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Local semi-professional or amateur organisations and competitions are often affiliated to their state organisations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 2003, the AFL became the *de facto* world governing body for Australian football when it pushed for the closure of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] There are also a number of affiliated organisations governing amateur clubs and competitions around the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In Australian football club competitions, the aim is to win the premiership (also known as the "flag"), which is typically decided by a finals series.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The teams that occupy the highest positions on the ladder after the home-and-away season play-off in a "semi-knockout" finals series, culminating in a single Grand Final match to determine the premiers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Between four and eight teams contest a finals series, typically using the AFL final eight system or a variation of the McIntyre system.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The team which finishes first on the ladder after the home-and-away season is referred to as the "minor premier", but this usually holds little stand-alone significance, other than receiving a better draw in the finals.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Some metropolitan leagues have several tiered divisions, with promotion of the lower division premiers and relegation of the upper division's last placed team at the end of each year.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The high level of interest shown by women in Australian football is considered unique among the world's football codes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It was the case in the 19th century, as it is in modern times, that women made up approximately half of total attendances at Australian football matches—a far greater proportion than, for example, the estimated 10 per cent of women that comprise British soccer crowds.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This has been attributed in part to the egalitarian character of Australian football's early years in public parks where women could mingle freely and support the game in various ways.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In terms of participation, there are occasional 19th-century references to women playing the sport, but it was not until the 1910s that the first organised women's teams and competitions appeared.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Women's state leagues emerged in the 1980s, and in 2013, the AFL announced plans to establish a national semi-professional women's competition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Amidst a surge in viewing interest and participation in women's football, the AFL pushed the founding date of the competition, named AFL Women's (AFLW), to 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Eight AFL clubs won licences to field sides in its inaugural season.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] By 2022, all 18 clubs fielded an AFLW side, and there will be 19 teams with the admission of Tasmania to the competition in 2028.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Many related games have emerged from Australian football, mainly with variations of contact to encourage greater participation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] These include Auskick (played by children aged between 5 and 12), kick-to-kick (and its variants end-to-end footy and marks up), rec footy, 9-a-side footy, masters Australian football, handball and longest-kick competitions.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Players outside Australia sometimes engage in related games adapted to available fields, like metro footy (played on gridiron fields) and Samoa rules (played on rugby fields).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] One such prominent example in use since 2018 is AFLX, a shortened variation of the game with seven players a side, played on a soccer-sized pitch.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The similarities between Australian football and the Irish sport of Gaelic football have allowed for the creation of a hybrid code known as international rules football.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The first international rules matches were contested in Ireland during the 1967 Australian Football World Tour.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Since then, various sets of compromise rules have been trialed, and in 1984 the International Rules Series commenced with national representative sides selected by Australia's state leagues (later by the AFL) and the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA).
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The competition became an annual event in 1998, but was postponed indefinitely in 2007 when the GAA pulled out due to Australia's severe and aggressive style of play.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] It resumed in Australia in 2008 under new rules to protect the player with the ball.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] During the colonial period, Australian rules was sometimes referred to as Australasian rules, reflecting its popularity in New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game was played outside Australasia as early as 1888 when Australians studying at Edinburgh University and London University formed teams and competed in London.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Further international exposure came that same year, when the first British rugby side to tour the Southern Hemisphere played Australian rules matches in both Australia and New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] By the early 20th century, it had spread with the Australian diaspora to South Africa, the United States and other parts of the Anglosphere; however this growth went into rapid decline during and after World War I, leading also to a decades long hiatus in New Zealand.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] After World War II, it experienced growth in the Pacific region, particularly in Papua New Guinea and Nauru, where it is now the national sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Today, the sport is played at an amateur level in various countries throughout the world.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Twenty-three countries have participated in the International Cup, which was held triennially in Australia from 2002 to 2017.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] International competition resumed in 2024 with three regional tournaments: the Transatlantic Cup, Asia Cup, and Pacific Cup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Nine countries have also participated in the AFL Europe Championship.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 2013, participation across AFL Europe's 21 member nations was more than 5,000 players, the majority of which are European nationals rather than Australian expats.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The sport also has a growing presence in India.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Over 20 countries have either affiliation or working agreements with the AFL.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Most present-day international amateur clubs and leagues are based in North America, Europe and Asia, with the oldest typically having originated in the 1980s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] That decade, the sport developed a cult following in the United States when matches were broadcast on the fledgling ESPN network.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Growing international interest has been assisted by exhibition matches, players switching between football codes, and Australia's multicultural makeup.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Many VFL/AFL players were born overseas, with a growing number recruited through various initiatives.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] One notable example is the Irish experiment, which, since the 1980s, has seen many Gaelic footballers leave the amateur GAA to play Australian rules professionally.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This has expanded to women's football, with 39 Irish players on AFLW lists for the 2025 season.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Although Australian rules football is not an Olympic sport, it was showcased at the MCG as part of the 1956 Summer Olympics, held in Melbourne.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In addition, when Brisbane hosted the 1982 Commonwealth Games, an exhibition match between Richmond and Carlton was held at the Gabba.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian football has attracted more overall interest among Australians than any other football code.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The 2024 AFL season saw an average attendance of 38,344 fans per match, making the AFL Australia's, and one of the world's best-attended sports leagues.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Also that year, data indicated 1,319,687 people, or 1 in 20 Australians, are members of an AFL club.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The most-visited sports website in Australia in 2023 was the AFL's, attracting 1.89 billion total visits.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Approximately 40% of Australians aged 14+ watch AFL matches on TV either occasionally or regularly.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The 2024 AFL Grand Final was that year's highest-rating free-to-air television broadcast in Australia, with an in-home audience of 4 million watching Seven's coverage; overall TV viewership reached at least 7,569,000.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The AFL's current TV broadcasting rights deal with Seven and Foxtel is worth an Australian record $4.5 billion.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In terms of participation, there were at least 581,000 registered players in Australia in 2024.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] This figure encompasses community football at junior, youth, and senior levels, as well as programs such as Footy 9s.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Among Australian children aged 0–14, it is the fifth most common sporting activity, behind swimming, soccer, basketball and gymnastics.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Women and girls account for 20% of all community football registrations.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian football has inspired works by many writers and poets, including C.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Dennis, Helen Garner, Peter Goldsworthy and Kerry Greenwood.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Historians Manning Clarke and Geoffrey Blainey have also written extensively on the sport.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Slang within Australian football has impacted Australian English more broadly, with a number of expressions taking on new meanings in non-sporting contexts, e.g., to "get a guernsey" is to gain recognition or approval, while "shirt-fronting" someone is to accost them.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In 1889, Australian impressionist painter Arthur Streeton captured football games *en plein air* for the 9 by 5 Impression Exhibition, titling one work *The National Game*.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Paintings by Sidney Nolan (*Footballer*, 1946) and John Brack (*Three of the Players*, 1953) helped to establish Australian football as a serious subject for modernists, and many Aboriginal artists have explored the game, often fusing it with the mythology of their region.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Vincent Namatjira won the 2020 Archibald Prize for his portrait of Adam Goodes.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In cartooning, WEG's VFL/AFL premiership posters—inaugurated in 1954—have achieved iconic status among Australian football fans.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Australian football statues can be found throughout the country, some based on famous photographs, among them Haydn Bunton Sr.'s leap, Jack Dyer's charge and Nicky Winmar lifting his jumper.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In the 1980s, a group of postmodern architects based in Melbourne began incorporating references to Australian football into their buildings, an example being Building 8 by Edmond and Corrigan.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Dance sequences based on Australian football feature heavily in Robert Helpmann's 1964 ballet *The Display*, his first and most famous work for the Australian Ballet.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] The game has also inspired well-known plays such as *And the Big Men Fly* (1963) by Alan Hopgood and David Williamson's *The Club* (1977), which was adapted into a 1980 film, directed by Bruce Beresford.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Mike Brady's 1979 hit "Up There Cazaly" is considered an Australian football anthem, and references to the sport can be found in works by popular musicians, from singer-songwriter Paul Kelly to the alternative rock band TISM.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Others, such as Tame Impala's Kevin Parker, have written songs for their favourite AFL club.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Many Australian football video games have been released, notably the AFL series.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] For the centenary of the VFL/AFL in 1996, the Australian Football Hall of Fame was established.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] That year, 136 significant figures across the various competitions were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Each years since the creation of the Hall of Fame, a panel selects a small group of players they deem worthy for this prestigious honour, resulting in a total number of more than 300 inductees as of 2024.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] In addition to the Hall of Fame, select members are chosen to receive the elite *Legend* status.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/australian-rules-football] Due to restrictions limiting the number of Legend status players to 10% of the total number of Hall of Fame inductees, there are currently only 32 players with the status in the Hall of Fame as of 2024.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali is the only Hindu-majority province in Indonesia, with 86.40% of the population adhering to Balinese Hinduism.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] It is renowned for its highly developed arts, including traditional and modern dance, sculpture, painting, leather, metalworking, and music.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Indonesian International Film Festival is held every year in Bali.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Other international events that have been held in Bali include Miss World 2013, the 2018 Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group, and the 2022 G20 summit.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In March 2017, Tripadvisor named Bali as the world's top destination in its Traveler's Choice award, which it earned once again in January 2021 and 2026.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali is part of the Coral Triangle, an area with high diversity of marine species, mainly fish and turtles.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In this area alone, over 500 reef-building coral species can be found.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] For comparison, this is about seven times as many as in the entire Caribbean.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali is the home of the Subak irrigation system, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] It is also home to a unified confederation of kingdoms composed of 10 traditional royal Balinese houses, each house ruling a specific geographic area.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The confederation is the successor of the Bali Kingdom.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The royal houses, which originated before Dutch colonisation, are not recognised by the government of Indonesia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The name *Bali* is attested in ancient Balinese inscriptions as part of the compound *Vāli-dvīpa* (or *Wāli-dvīpa*), where Sanskrit *dvīpa* (Sanskrit: द्वीप) means "island".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] One of the earliest attestations of *Vāli-dvīpa* occurs in the Belanjong (Blanjong) pillar inscription, dated to Saka year 835 / Phalguna month, under King Sri Kesari Warmadewa (c.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The precise meaning of the element *Vāli* in *Vāli-dvīpa* is not certain.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali was inhabited around 2000 BC by Austronesian peoples who migrated originally from the island of Taiwan to Southeast Asia and Oceania through Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Culturally and linguistically, the Balinese are closely related to the people of the Indonesian archipelago, Malaysia, Brunei, the Philippines, and Oceania.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Stone tools dating from this time have been found near the village of Cekik in the island's west.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In ancient Bali, nine Hindu sects existed: the Pasupata, Bhairawa, Siwa Shidanta, Vaishnava, Bodha, Brahma, Resi, Sora, and Ganapatya.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Each sect revered a specific deity as its personal Godhead.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Inscriptions from 896 and 911 do not mention a king until 914, when Sri Kesarivarma, a contemporary of the Kesari dynasty in the Kalinga Kingdom of ancient India, is mentioned.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] They also reveal an independent Bali, with a distinct dialect, being influenced by the Sanskrit and Pali languages, where Buddhism and Shaivism were practiced simultaneously.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Mpu Sindok's great-granddaughter, Mahendradatta (Gunapriyadharmapatni), married the Bali king Udayana Warmadewa (Dharmodayanavarmadeva) around 989, giving birth to Airlangga around 1001.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] This marriage also brought more Hinduism and Javanese culture to Bali.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Princess Sakalendukirana appeared in 1098.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Suradhipa reigned from 1115 to 1119, and Jayasakti from 1146 until 1150.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Jayapangus appears on inscriptions between 1178 and 1181, while Adikuntiketana and his son Paramesvara appear in 1204.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Balinese culture was strongly influenced by Indian, Chinese, and particularly Kalinga Hindu culture, beginning around the 1st century AD.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The name *Bali dwipa* ("Bali island") has been discovered from various inscriptions, including the Blanjong pillar inscription written by Sri Kesari Warmadewa in 914 AD, and mentioning **Walidwipa**.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] It was during this time that the people developed their complex irrigation system, *subak,* to grow rice in wet-field cultivation.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Some religious and cultural traditions still practiced today can be traced to this period.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Hindu-Buddhist Majapahit Empire (1293–1520 AD) on eastern Java founded a Balinese colony in 1343.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The uncle of Hayam Wuruk is mentioned in the charters of 1384–86.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Mass Javanese immigration to Bali occurred in the next century when the Majapahit Empire fell in 1520.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali's government then became an independent collection of Hindu kingdoms, which led to a Balinese national identity and major enhancements in culture, arts, and economy.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The nation with various kingdoms became independent for up to 386 years until 1906, when the Dutch subjugated and repulsed the natives for economic control and took it over.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The first known European contact with Bali is thought to have been made in 1512, when a Portuguese expedition led by Antonio Abreu and Francisco Serrão sighted its northern shores.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] It was the first expedition of a series of bi-annual fleets to the Moluccas, which, throughout the 16th century, travelled along the coasts of the Sunda Islands.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Bali was also mapped in 1512, in the chart of Francisco Rodrigues, aboard the expedition.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In 1585, a ship foundered off the Bukit Peninsula and left a few Portuguese in the service of Dewa Agung.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In 1597, the Dutch merchant-explorer Cornelis de Houtman arrived at Bali, and the Dutch East India Company was established in 1602.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Dutch government expanded its control across the Indonesian archipelago during the second half of the 19th century.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Dutch political and economic control over Bali began in the 1840s on the island's north coast when the Dutch pitted various competing Balinese realms against each other.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In the late 1890s, struggles between Balinese kingdoms on the island's south were exploited by the Dutch to increase their control.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In June 1860, the famous Welsh naturalist, Alfred Russel Wallace, travelled to Bali from Singapore, landing at Buleleng on the north coast of the island.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Wallace's trip to Bali was instrumental in helping him devise his Wallace Line theory.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Wallace Line is a faunal boundary that runs through the strait between Bali and Lombok.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Dutch mounted large naval and ground assaults at the Sanur region in 1906 and were met by the thousands of members of the royal family and their followers, who, rather than yield to the superior Dutch force, committed ritual suicide (*puputan*) to avoid the humiliation of surrender.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Despite Dutch demands for surrender, an estimated 200 Balinese killed themselves rather than surrender.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In the Dutch intervention in Bali, a similar mass suicide occurred in the face of a Dutch assault in Klungkung.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Afterward, the Dutch governors exercised administrative control over the island, but local control over religion and culture generally remained intact.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Dutch rule over Bali came later and was never as well established as in other parts of Indonesia, such as Java and Maluku.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In the 1930s, anthropologists Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson, artists Miguel Covarrubias and Walter Spies, and musicologist Colin McPhee all spent time here.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Their accounts of the island and its peoples created a Western image of Bali as "an enchanted land of aesthetes at peace with themselves and nature".
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Soon after, Western tourists began to visit the island.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The film, which mostly consisted of scenes of topless Balinese women, was a great success in 1932, and was perhaps the main catalyst for the popularity of Bali among tourists.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The Dutch also dedicated significant efforts to implement *Baliseering* (lit.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] 'Balinization') politics to maintain traditions on the island, as well as preventing the Islamization of the Islamic sultanates from Java and banning Christian missionaries' activities.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] Imperial Japan occupied Bali during World War II.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] It was not originally a target in their Netherlands East Indies Campaign; however, as the airfields on Borneo were inoperative due to heavy rains, the Imperial Japanese Army decided to occupy Bali, which did not suffer from comparable weather.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The island had no regular Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) troops.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] There was only a Native Auxiliary Corps *Prajoda* (Korps Prajoda) consisting of about 600 native soldiers and several Dutch KNIL officers under the command of KNIL Lieutenant Colonel W.P.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] On 19 February 1942, the Japanese forces landed near the town of Sanoer (Sanur) and the island was quickly captured.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] During the Japanese occupation, a Balinese military officer, I Gusti Ngurah Rai, formed a Balinese 'freedom army'.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] The harsh treatment of the Balinese by the Japanese occupation forces fomented more resentment than the former Dutch colonial rulers.
[src:asian-australian-football-championships/bali-p01] In 1945, Bali was liberated by the British 5th Infantry Division under the command of Major-General Robert Mansergh, who took the Japanese surrender.
